  "slug": "pecan-pie-classic",
  "title": "Classic pecan pie",
  "subtitle": "Sticky, dark pecan filling on a shortcrust base",
  "excerpt": "The American Southern classic: a shortcrust pastry shell filled with a sticky, dark pecan custard of golden syrup, brown sugar, butter, eggs and toasted pecans. One 23 cm pie, serving eight.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Karo Cookbook (1908, public domain US trade pamphlet): documents the canonical pecan pie filling, golden syrup (or American 'corn syrup'), eggs, butter, sugar, pecans. Sarah Hutson and Mrs. Lincoln, Mrs. Lincoln's Boston Cook Book (1884), Project Gutenberg: documents shortcrust pastry blind-baking for syrup-based fillings.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Pecan pie has two parts: a blind-baked shortcrust shell and a sticky filling of golden syrup, brown sugar, melted butter, eggs and toasted pecans, poured in and baked until the centre just sets. The pecans float on top during the bake; the filling sets dark and glossy underneath.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Toast the pecans before they go in; the heat draws out the oils and deepens the flavour. The classic recipe uses American corn syrup, which has the same role as British golden syrup. Either works.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
